# Accessibility Guidelines

## ARIA and Semantic HTML
- Use semantic HTML elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`) over generic `<div>` elements
- Implement proper ARIA attributes (`aria-label`, `aria-describedby`, `aria-expanded`, etc.)
- Use `role` attributes when semantic HTML is not sufficient
- Ensure proper heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3) for screen readers
- Use `alt` attributes for all images with descriptive text

## Keyboard Navigation
- Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- Implement proper tab order and focus management
- Use `tabindex` appropriately (avoid positive values unless necessary)
- Provide visible focus indicators for keyboard users
- Implement keyboard shortcuts for common actions when appropriate

## Color and Contrast
- Maintain sufficient color contrast ratios (minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text)
- Don't rely solely on color to convey information
- Use the predefined color palette from `tailwind.config.ts`
- Test with color blindness simulators when possible
- Provide alternative indicators for color-coded information

## Screen Reader Support
- Use `aria-live` regions for dynamic content updates
- Implement proper form labels and error associations
- Provide skip links for main content navigation
- Use `aria-hidden` for decorative elements that don't add meaning
- Test with actual screen readers when possible

## Form Accessibility
- Associate labels with form controls using `for` and `id` attributes
- Provide clear error messages and associate them with form fields
- Use `aria-required` and `aria-invalid` for form validation
- Implement proper focus management for form interactions
- Ensure form controls are properly grouped and labeled